>>HATSIS: Henbane is--
we actually today,

00:44:24.010 --> 00:44:27.670 align:middle line:84%
just like Coca-Cola used
to have cocaine in it.

00:44:27.670 --> 00:44:29.290 align:middle line:84%
That's where
Coca-Cola comes from.

00:44:29.290 --> 00:44:32.550 align:middle line:84%
We actually have the
historical residue

00:44:32.550 --> 00:44:35.970 align:middle line:84%
of when henbane was put to
make beer strong in the name

00:44:35.970 --> 00:44:39.850 align:middle line:84%
"pilsner." "Bilsen"
is German for henbane.

00:44:39.850 --> 00:44:44.000 align:middle line:84%
So a bilsenkraut is a beer
that had henbane in it.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:46.000 align:middle line:10%
But once the henbane
was taken out,

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:47.140 align:middle line:10%
there were laws against it.

00:44:47.140 --> 00:44:48.770 align:middle line:10%
>> REGINA: What was the
effect of the henbane?

00:44:48.770 --> 00:44:50.020 align:middle line:10%
>>HATSIS: Ooh, henbane is odd.

00:44:50.020 --> 00:44:52.080 align:middle line:10%
>> REGINA: In your beer.

00:44:52.080 --> 00:44:54.440 align:middle line:10%
They called it a
crazy-making plant.

00:44:54.440 --> 00:44:57.220 align:middle line:84%
But it will cause
hallucinations.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:45:00.990 align:middle line:84%
It will cause-- I've
actually inhaled henbane.

00:45:00.990 --> 00:45:04.120 align:middle line:90%
Kids, don't inhale henbane.

00:45:04.120 --> 00:45:05.990 align:middle line:90%
It's pretty interesting.

00:45:05.990 --> 00:45:09.000 align:middle line:90%
Henbane is very powerful.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:12.344 align:middle line:84%
It causes, at least
for me it was--

00:45:12.344 --> 00:45:13.760 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to
get into all that,

00:45:13.760 --> 00:45:16.440 align:middle line:90%
but I wouldn't recommend it.

00:45:16.440 --> 00:45:19.700 align:middle line:10%
>> REGINA: OK, so no on--
cross off on the henbane,

00:45:19.700 --> 00:45:22.080 align:middle line:10%
and don't make your home
brew with it, either.

00:45:22.080 --> 00:45:25.850 align:middle line:84%
>>HATSIS: Oh, no, you can,
just don't use too much.

00:45:25.850 --> 00:45:28.502 align:middle line:84%
It's just like anything,
dose, set, and setting.

00:45:28.502 --> 00:45:30.210 align:middle line:84%
Don't take too much,
have a good mindset,

00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:31.390 align:middle line:90%
and be in a good place.

00:45:31.390 --> 00:45:33.240 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: What about mandrake?

00:45:33.240 --> 00:45:34.360 align:middle line:90%
>>HATSIS: Mandrake.

00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:37.120 align:middle line:10%
Mandrake was probably
the most popular plant

00:45:37.120 --> 00:45:41.260 align:middle line:10%
found in love
filters, because it's

00:45:41.260 --> 00:45:46.960 align:middle line:10%
also highly psychoactive
and easy to come by.

00:45:46.960 --> 00:45:49.370 align:middle line:10%
Because mandrake
actually will continue

00:45:49.370 --> 00:45:50.780 align:middle line:10%
to grow in the same area.

00:45:50.780 --> 00:45:55.700 align:middle line:10%
That's one of the linguistic
ideas of where the name comes

00:45:55.700 --> 00:45:59.140 align:middle line:10%
from, is mandra agora, which
means "usual meeting place."

00:45:59.140 --> 00:46:04.360 align:middle line:10%
And mandrake was a
big addition into--

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:06.640 align:middle line:10%
>> REGINA: It had
ecstasy-like effects?

00:46:06.640 --> 00:46:07.980 align:middle line:10%
>>HATSIS: Yeah, it can.

00:46:07.980 --> 00:46:10.202 align:middle line:10%
It can, usually if
mixed with opium.

00:46:10.202 --> 00:46:12.660 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yeah, I was going
to get to this mix in a little

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:14.620 align:middle line:84%
but that was used
on these sponges.

00:46:14.620 --> 00:46:15.960 align:middle line:84%
>>HATSIS: Oh, yeah, the
soporific sponges, yeah.

00:46:15.960 --> 00:46:17.918 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yeah, I found
it really interesting.

00:46:17.918 --> 00:46:20.560 align:middle line:84%
>>HATSIS: That's actually
how we-- the first references

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:25.220 align:middle line:84%
we have to the use of
ointments by shamans

00:46:25.220 --> 00:46:29.530 align:middle line:84%
comes from people talking
about the medical use of them.

00:46:29.530 --> 00:46:32.440 align:middle line:84%
And one of the more
important things about that

00:46:32.440 --> 00:46:35.070 align:middle line:84%
is that they weren't
trying to prove at the time

00:46:35.070 --> 00:46:38.250 align:middle line:84%
that people used these
ointments for this purpose,

00:46:38.250 --> 00:46:41.870 align:middle line:84%
again, because it's before
the witch stereotype.

00:46:41.870 --> 00:46:44.210 align:middle line:84%
One guy I write about
named Alonso Tostado, who

00:46:44.210 --> 00:46:46.970 align:middle line:90%
was the bishop of Avila, Spain.

00:46:46.970 --> 00:46:52.100 align:middle line:84%
He wrote commentaries, biblical
literalist commentaries.

00:46:52.100 --> 00:46:54.020 align:middle line:84%
Biblical literalism
is just the idea

00:46:54.020 --> 00:46:56.630 align:middle line:84%
that the stories in the Bible
were true not based on face

00:46:56.630 --> 00:46:57.984 align:middle line:90%
but based on reason.

00:46:57.984 --> 00:46:59.400 align:middle line:84%
I think I just
said based on face.

00:46:59.400 --> 00:47:00.070 align:middle line:90%
I meant faith.

00:47:00.070 --> 00:47:01.236 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Faith, we got it.

00:47:01.236 --> 00:47:02.710 align:middle line:90%
>>HATSIS: Based on faith.

00:47:02.710 --> 00:47:04.880 align:middle line:90%
But they were based on reason.

00:47:04.880 --> 00:47:08.370 align:middle line:84%
So this guy's
writing a commentary

00:47:08.370 --> 00:47:10.920 align:middle line:84%
on the book of Genesis,
and he's trying to decide,

00:47:10.920 --> 00:47:13.290 align:middle line:84%
how could God, or I guess
in this sense Yahweh,

00:47:13.290 --> 00:47:16.490 align:middle line:84%
take a rib from Adam to
create Eve without causing him

00:47:16.490 --> 00:47:17.450 align:middle line:90%
any pain?

00:47:17.450 --> 00:47:21.080 align:middle line:84%
So his literalist reason,
his rationale for this,

00:47:21.080 --> 00:47:24.390 align:middle line:84%
is, oh, God must have used
one of those medical ointments

00:47:24.390 --> 00:47:26.700 align:middle line:84%
on Adam to cast him
into a deep sleep.

00:47:26.700 --> 00:47:29.000 align:middle line:84%
And he could pull the rib,
and Adam would be fine.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:30.884 align:middle line:84%
And then he has this
off-the-cuff comment

00:47:30.884 --> 00:47:32.550 align:middle line:84%
just saying, and by
the way, we actually

00:47:32.550 --> 00:47:37.280 align:middle line:84%
know that certain women actually
know about these ointments,

00:47:37.280 --> 00:47:40.000 align:middle line:84%
and they tend to fly away
and imagine that they're

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:40.400 align:middle line:90%
having these experiences.

00:47:40.400 --> 00:47:41.983 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So it
gets linked together.

00:47:41.983 --> 00:47:43.450 align:middle line:84%
But it was
interesting, because we

00:47:43.450 --> 00:47:46.730 align:middle line:84%
think of surgery in ancient
times and think, oh, my God,

00:47:46.730 --> 00:47:48.030 align:middle line:90%
how did they manage it?

00:47:48.030 --> 00:47:49.320 align:middle line:90%
They did manage it.

00:47:49.320 --> 00:47:51.990 align:middle line:84%
They put these together
and had the sponges,

00:47:51.990 --> 00:47:53.010 align:middle line:90%
as I recall you said.

00:47:53.010 --> 00:47:55.467 align:middle line:84%
They were stuffed up their
nose to put them into--

00:47:55.467 --> 00:47:56.550 align:middle line:90%
>>HATSIS: To a deep sleep.

00:47:56.550 --> 00:47:58.760 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: --a deep, deep sleep
so that they could have surgery

00:47:58.760 --> 00:47:59.820 align:middle line:90%
performed on them.

00:47:59.820 --> 00:48:02.130 align:middle line:84%
But one other another
thing I found interesting

00:48:02.130 --> 00:48:07.060 align:middle line:84%
was how they were used for a
kind of merciful execution.

00:48:07.060 --> 00:48:09.290 align:middle line:84%
Your wrote about that
in the book at one point

00:48:09.290 --> 00:48:13.310 align:middle line:84%
that someone being executed
was actually administered

00:48:13.310 --> 00:48:15.880 align:middle line:90%
some of these calmatives.

00:48:15.880 --> 00:48:17.780 align:middle line:84%
>>HATSIS: At times
they would be.

00:48:17.780 --> 00:48:19.280 align:middle line:84%
Again, it's that
case-by-case basis.

00:48:19.280 --> 00:48:20.890 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Yeah, but
you would never--

00:48:20.890 --> 00:48:23.860 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't put those two
together in ancient times,

00:48:23.860 --> 00:48:26.620 align:middle line:84%
that there would be a merciful
process to one's execution.

00:48:26.620 --> 00:48:27.786 align:middle line:90%
>>HATSIS: Well, it depended.

00:48:27.786 --> 00:48:31.820 align:middle line:84%
If you were a rich individual,
then there might be.

00:48:31.820 --> 00:48:33.766 align:middle line:84%
One of the more
interesting things

00:48:33.766 --> 00:48:36.140 align:middle line:84%
I found out that I was not
aware of at all in my research

00:48:36.140 --> 00:48:38.360 align:middle line:84%
is that up until
about the 1300s,

00:48:38.360 --> 00:48:42.950 align:middle line:84%
the majority of people burned
for sorcery were men, rich men,

00:48:42.950 --> 00:48:45.160 align:middle line:84%
and it was a way to just
get them out of the picture.

00:48:45.160 --> 00:48:45.720 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Really?

00:48:45.720 --> 00:48:46.520 align:middle line:90%
>>HATSIS: Yeah.

00:48:46.520 --> 00:48:48.940 align:middle line:84%
And they might be
administered these things.

00:48:48.940 --> 00:48:53.850 align:middle line:84%
In fact, even a
pope, Pope Boniface,

00:48:53.850 --> 00:48:58.280 align:middle line:84%
was accused of witchcraft, found
innocent, then after he died,

00:48:58.280 --> 00:49:01.560 align:middle line:84%
it was then decided that
he was actually guilty.

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:04.070 align:middle line:84%
They disinterred the
remains and burned them.

00:49:04.070 --> 00:49:05.630 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:49:05.630 --> 00:49:10.140 align:middle line:90%
So they could be administered.

00:49:10.140 --> 00:49:14.540 align:middle line:84%
There was also a manual
in the 1600s, [INAUDIBLE],

00:49:14.540 --> 00:49:17.460 align:middle line:84%
where a guy said
that in some cases,

00:49:17.460 --> 00:49:20.800 align:middle line:84%
a torturer would actually
just drug the person

00:49:20.800 --> 00:49:26.144 align:middle line:84%
being inquested just to make
her say outlandish things.

00:49:26.144 --> 00:49:27.810 align:middle line:84%
Because it's like,
I'm going to give you

00:49:27.810 --> 00:49:30.199 align:middle line:84%
this drug that perhaps
you've never taken before,

00:49:30.199 --> 00:49:31.990 align:middle line:84%
and it's going to have
this psychic effect,

00:49:31.990 --> 00:49:34.063 align:middle line:84%
and you're going to
start really feeling it.

00:49:34.063 --> 00:49:35.800 align:middle line:84%
And now I'm going to bring all
the theologians, say, look,

00:49:35.800 --> 00:49:36.770 align:middle line:90%
she's crazy.

00:49:36.770 --> 00:49:39.570 align:middle line:90%
See, look at how nuts she is.

00:49:39.570 --> 00:49:41.860 align:middle line:84%
They were used in so
many different ways,

00:49:41.860 --> 00:49:43.176 align:middle line:90%
these substances.

00:49:43.176 --> 00:49:45.550 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well, we're coming
toward the end of our time,

00:49:45.550 --> 00:49:49.340 align:middle line:84%
and I don't want to go without
getting to the-- Waldensian?

00:49:49.340 --> 00:49:50.530 align:middle line:90%
>>HATSIS: Mhm.

00:49:50.530 --> 00:49:52.990 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Waldensian
barbes and sorceresses.

00:49:52.990 --> 00:49:55.590 align:middle line:84%
Because it seemed they
held a unique spot.

00:49:55.590 --> 00:49:56.500 align:middle line:90%
>>HATSIS: They did.

00:49:56.500 --> 00:49:59.220 align:middle line:84%
The barbes were mostly
traveling physicians.

00:49:59.220 --> 00:50:03.030 align:middle line:84%
And they went out to remote
places and the backwoods areas

00:50:03.030 --> 00:50:07.790 align:middle line:84%
of Europe to preach their
gospel, the Waldensian gospel.

00:50:07.790 --> 00:50:12.619 align:middle line:84%
And that was not OK, because
they were considered heretics.

00:50:12.619 --> 00:50:14.160 align:middle line:84%
At first when they
were first formed,

00:50:14.160 --> 00:50:16.810 align:middle line:84%
they were actually praised by
the church for their piety.

00:50:16.810 --> 00:50:20.130 align:middle line:84%
And then later on when they
grew too powerful and they had

00:50:20.130 --> 00:50:22.780 align:middle line:84%
attracted such a following, it's
like, oh, well, they gotta--

00:50:22.780 --> 00:50:24.200 align:middle line:90%
we gotta to get rid of them.

00:50:24.200 --> 00:50:28.860 align:middle line:10%
And some of the
backwoods areas--

00:50:28.860 --> 00:50:32.710 align:middle line:10%
I had mentioned earlier
Billia la Castagna, who

00:50:32.710 --> 00:50:35.830 align:middle line:10%
seems to have been a
Waldensian and also

00:50:35.830 --> 00:50:40.280 align:middle line:10%
a wise woman in the
same sense of like today

00:50:40.280 --> 00:50:43.120 align:middle line:10%
your brother isn't
just your brother.

00:50:43.120 --> 00:50:45.110 align:middle line:84%
He might also be the
husband of somebody.

00:50:45.110 --> 00:50:49.610 align:middle line:84%
He might also be an artist, and
in his day job he's a mechanic.

00:50:49.610 --> 00:50:53.294 align:middle line:84%
Different people-- if there
was one thing that I was trying

00:50:53.294 --> 00:50:55.210 align:middle line:84%
to get across in my book
by the stories I tell

00:50:55.210 --> 00:50:58.520 align:middle line:84%
is that these are not
flat, individual people.

00:50:58.520 --> 00:50:59.840 align:middle line:90%
They're not flat.

00:50:59.840 --> 00:51:02.050 align:middle line:90%
They had hopes, desires, dreams.

00:51:02.050 --> 00:51:03.590 align:middle line:90%
They were multi-leveled.

00:51:03.590 --> 00:51:04.390 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Complex.

00:51:04.390 --> 00:51:06.470 align:middle line:84%
>>HATSIS: Yeah, they were
just like we are today.

00:51:06.470 --> 00:51:09.480 align:middle line:84%
So to call someone-- it all
depends on the perspective.

00:51:09.480 --> 00:51:14.390 align:middle line:84%
Like Billia, to her
people, she was a healer.

00:51:14.390 --> 00:51:16.810 align:middle line:84%
To the clergy,
she was a heretic.

00:51:16.810 --> 00:51:20.080 align:middle line:84%
To somebody else that maybe
her spell didn't work on,

00:51:20.080 --> 00:51:21.550 align:middle line:90%
she was a sorceress.

00:51:21.550 --> 00:51:23.830 align:middle line:84%
And in a sense, yeah,
she was all those things.

00:51:23.830 --> 00:51:26.750 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And why were they
particularly either feared

00:51:26.750 --> 00:51:28.567 align:middle line:84%
or respected, this
particular group?

00:51:28.567 --> 00:51:29.650 align:middle line:90%
>>HATSIS: The Waldensians?

00:51:29.650 --> 00:51:30.450 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Mhm.

00:51:30.450 --> 00:51:34.730 align:middle line:84%
>>HATSIS: Because of how
really prevalent they were.

00:51:34.730 --> 00:51:38.970 align:middle line:84%
The Cathars had been stamped
out in the Albigensian Crusade

00:51:38.970 --> 00:51:40.210 align:middle line:90%
in the 1200s.

00:51:40.210 --> 00:51:41.960 align:middle line:84%
But the Waldensians
had survived.

00:51:41.960 --> 00:51:46.080 align:middle line:84%
So much of this has to do
with that kind of competition

00:51:46.080 --> 00:51:48.680 align:middle line:84%
to the church, the
wise women that were

00:51:48.680 --> 00:51:52.050 align:middle line:90%
giving different medical cures.

00:51:52.050 --> 00:51:53.780 align:middle line:84%
They were a competition
to the church,

00:51:53.780 --> 00:51:54.946 align:middle line:90%
so we gotta get rid of them.

00:51:54.946 --> 00:51:57.757 align:middle line:84%
The Waldensians, they were a
competition to the spirituality

00:51:57.757 --> 00:51:59.840 align:middle line:84%
or whatever the-- so we've
got to get rid of them.

00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:03.160 align:middle line:84%
The Waldensians
were very powerful.

00:52:03.160 --> 00:52:05.080 align:middle line:84%
They attracted a
large following.

00:52:05.080 --> 00:52:07.070 align:middle line:90%
And so did these wise women.

00:52:07.070 --> 00:52:11.600 align:middle line:84%
And that's why they were each
in their own regard stamped out.

00:52:11.600 --> 00:52:13.900 align:middle line:84%
But then again, you
have certain wise women

00:52:13.900 --> 00:52:15.650 align:middle line:84%
who would be
Waldensians, and that's

00:52:15.650 --> 00:52:18.760 align:middle line:84%
how you see the stereotype
being brought over.

00:52:18.760 --> 00:52:24.630 align:middle line:84%
In fact, in an anonymous
tract titled [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:24.630 --> 00:52:27.570 align:middle line:84%
Gazari is an old slang
word for witches,

00:52:27.570 --> 00:52:29.230 align:middle line:90%
but it actually means Cathars.

00:52:29.230 --> 00:52:32.260 align:middle line:84%
So what we're seeing is that
is that witches are being

00:52:32.260 --> 00:52:34.940 align:middle line:90%
called heretics at this time.

00:52:34.940 --> 00:52:38.200 align:middle line:84%
And just from a
linguistic standpoint,

00:52:38.200 --> 00:52:40.700 align:middle line:84%
you could actually watch
that transition happen

00:52:40.700 --> 00:52:42.710 align:middle line:90%
from the heretic to the witch.

00:52:42.710 --> 00:52:45.446 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Well, this to me
was a fascinating journey.

00:52:45.446 --> 00:52:47.320 align:middle line:84%
And how does this book
compare to other books

00:52:47.320 --> 00:52:50.170 align:middle line:90%
on entheogens in your mind?

00:52:50.170 --> 00:52:53.670 align:middle line:10%
>>HATSIS: I think it
just fills in that gap.

00:52:53.670 --> 00:52:56.910 align:middle line:10%
Recently there were a lot
of different documentaries

00:52:56.910 --> 00:53:01.060 align:middle line:10%
out that span historical drug
use on the History Channel.

00:53:01.060 --> 00:53:04.470 align:middle line:84%
One just came out that
featured that guy-- what's

00:53:04.470 --> 00:53:08.780 align:middle line:84%
that show called in New Mexico
with the-- "Breaking Bad."

00:53:08.780 --> 00:53:09.697 align:middle line:90%
It's some guy on that.

00:53:09.697 --> 00:53:11.238 align:middle line:84%
He did this whole
thing, and he talks

00:53:11.238 --> 00:53:13.649 align:middle line:84%
about the Eleusinian Rites
and everything and everybody.

00:53:13.649 --> 00:53:15.690 align:middle line:84%
And they talk about ancient
Greece, ancient Rome,

00:53:15.690 --> 00:53:18.580 align:middle line:84%
and then they skip over the
witches and the alchemists,

00:53:18.580 --> 00:53:23.030 align:middle line:84%
and they go right to people
in Victorian times using opium

00:53:23.030 --> 00:53:24.340 align:middle line:90%
and then the modern drug war.

00:53:24.340 --> 00:53:27.400 align:middle line:84%
And it's like, no, there's
this whole section there.

00:53:27.400 --> 00:53:31.340 align:middle line:84%
So for me, it just
fills in a gap

00:53:31.340 --> 00:53:35.500 align:middle line:84%
and shows that yeah, there
is a tradition in the West,

00:53:35.500 --> 00:53:36.820 align:middle line:90%
and it did survive.

00:53:36.820 --> 00:53:38.125 align:middle line:90%
They just called it witchcraft.

00:53:38.125 --> 00:53:40.250 align:middle line:84%
And that's why we don't
really know about it today.

00:53:40.250 --> 00:53:41.130 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't witchcraft.

00:53:41.130 --> 00:53:45.472 align:middle line:84%
It was an entheogenic practice
to worship the great mother.

00:53:45.472 --> 00:53:47.930 align:middle line:84%
